Hi Juan,



HyperNEAT excels at exploiting geometric properties of a given=
 domain. In the MCC experiments as well as most of the original novelty sea=
rch experiments, a maze navigation domain was employed. If the maze navigat=
or agent and its corresponding neural substrate was setup such that HyperNE=
AT could exploit placement geometry in the agent=E2=80=99s sensors and effe=
ctors, it seems plausible that HyperNEAT might offer an advantage; however,=
 that hasn=E2=80=99t been verified empirically for MCC (not sure about nove=
lty search). 



That being said, the question of whether HyperNEAT or ES-=
HyperNEAT would be better than NEAT is more dependent on the domain in ques=
tion. If the domain is one that would benefit from the explicit geometric e=
ncoding, then HyperNEAT may be a natural choice. If there are no relevant g=
eometric regularities in the domain, this may make it difficult to craft a =
substrate and NEAT might be more appropriate. In principle, either could be=
 used with novelty search or MCC.



